HIS103Y1-Y-20205.courseTitle: Statecraft and Strategy: An Introduction to the History of International Relations
HIS103Y1-Y-20205.courseDescription: An analysis of the development of the international system, from 1648 to 1945, which highlights the role of war as an instrument of national policy, as a determinant of the system of states and as a threat to international society.
HIS103Y1-Y-20205.exclusion: Any 100-level HIS course, with the exception of AP, IB, CAPE, or GCE transfer credits.

HIS241H1-S-20205.courseDescription: An introduction to modern European history from Napoleon to the outbreak of World War I. Important political, economic, social, and intellectual changes in France, Germany, Austria-Hungary, Italy, and other countries are discussed: revolution of 1848, Italian and German unification, racism and imperialism, the evolution of science, art, and culture, labour protest, and the coming of war.
HIS241H1-S-20205.webTimetableInstructions: Course will be delivered both asynchronously and synchronously

HIS264H1-F-20205.courseDescription: This course introduces key issues in Canadian history and foundational principles of historical analysis. It is primarily designed for potential History majors/specialists. It is not a comprehensive survey. Examples serve to deepen analysis and introduce important methods and debates, preparing students for upper year courses in Canadian history.

HIS280Y1-Y-20205.courseDescription: A broad overview of the history of China from earliest times to the present. The emphasis is on how the meaning of China and the Chinese people have changed through history.
HIS280Y1-Y-20205.webTimetableInstructions: Course will be delivered both asynchronously and synchronously

HIS292H1-S-20205.courseDescription: A survey of Latin American history from the wars of independence to the present day.
HIS292H1-S-20205.webTimetableInstructions: Course will be delivered both asynchronously and synchronously

HIS343H1-S-20205.courseDescription: An introduction to the historical origins and evolution of modern intelligence services. Topics to be studied include: intelligence in wartime; technological change; intelligence failures; covert operations; counter-espionage; the future of spying. The impact of the popular culture, both in fiction and film is also examined.
HIS343H1-S-20205.recommendedPreparation: HIS103Y1 or an equivalent introduction to modern international relations

HIS368H1-F-20205.courseDescription: Introduction to the political, social and religious history of early modern England, Scotland and Ireland. Particular attention will be paid to the history of the monarchy, the Protestant Reformation, gender issues and relations between different parts of the British Isles.

HIS377H1-S-20205.courseDescription: A survey of the history of American foreign relations from 1898 to the present. Themes include imperial expansion and the uses of power; the relationship of business and government in U.S. foreign policy; and the role of culture and ideas in Americas relations with the world.

HIS385H1-F-20205.courseDescription: A study of political, economic, and social change in the British colony of Hong Kong from 1842 until the present day.
HIS385H1-F-20205.exclusion: Students cannot take both the Y and H version of HIS385

HIS389H1-F-20205.courseDescription: In-depth examination of historical issues. Content in any given year depends on instructor. See History website for more details.
HIS389H1-F-20205.prerequisite: 9.0 FCEs including 1.0 FCE HIS course. Further pre-requisites vary from year to year, consult the department.

HIS393H1-F-20205.courseDescription: Explores implications for history and its methods of the shift from print to digital sources. Imparts introductory skills in the manipulation digital media, such as the use of maps, GIS and big data.
HIS393H1-F-20205.prerequisite: 200-level History course or one of WDW235H1/WDW236H1
HIS393H1-F-20205.exclusion: HIS389H1 (Topics in History: Digital History), offered in Summer 2015, Winter 2016, and Winter 2017
HIS393H1-F-20205.webTimetableInstructions: Course will be delivered both asynchronously and synchronously

HIS406H1-F-20205.courseDescription: An in-depth examination of issues in gender history. Content in any given year depends on instructor. See History website for more details.
HIS406H1-F-20205.webTimetableInstructions: Course will be delivered both asynchronously and synchronously

LEC-0101.subtitle: Gender in East and Southeast Asia
